Michael’. The Anglicized form was sometimes abbreviated into   Melville  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Melville was born about 1428, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas Melville. She died in 1488, in Pittendriech, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"ABT 1428–1488":"umbes 1428–1488","–Male":"Surnud","1440–1479":"1440–1479","1428–1488":"1428–1488","1479":"1479","1488":"1488","1440":"1440","ABT 1428":"umbes 1428","1428":"1428","Melville, Mid-Lothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Hawkhead, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Hawkhead, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Melville Castle, Melville, Pittendriech, Lasswade, Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland":"Pittendriech, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1428–1488":"noin 1428–1488","–Male":"Kuollut","1440–1479":"1440–1479","1428–1488":"1428–1488","1479":"1479","1488":"1488","1440":"1440","ABT 1428":"noin 1428","1428":"1428","Melville, Mid-Lothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kun